We need ability to handle non 200 response. Currently i handle this with overried of _run_task:
    def _run_task(self, task, response):
        """
        Finding callback specified by `task['callback']`
        raising status error for it if needed.
        """
        process = task.get('process', {})
        callback = process.get('callback', '__call__')
        if not hasattr(self, callback):
            raise NotImplementedError("self.%s() not implemented!" % callback)

        function = getattr(self, callback)
        # do not run_func when 304
        if response.status_code == 304 and not getattr(function, '_catch_status_code_error', False):
            return None
        if not getattr(function, '_catch_status_code_error', False) and response.status_code != 404:
            response.raise_for_status()
        return self._run_func(function, response, task)

But i dunno maybe there is more nice way to this?

## Expected Behavior
Even if the bounding box is not square, it should be able to get a properly bounded bounding box.

## Current Behavior
If the bounding box is not square, there is a problem with the rotated bounding box.

## Steps to Reproduce

```
    std::vector<dlib::matrix<unsigned char>> images;
    dlib::matrix<unsigned char> image;
    dlib::load_jpeg(image, "image path");
    images.emplace_back(image);

    std::vector<std::vector<dlib::rectangle>> bboxes{
    std::vector<dlib::rectangle>{ dlib::rectangle(100, 100, 200, 300)} }; // not square

    dlib::matrix<double, 2, 1> angles = { 0, 0.5 * M_PI };
    dlib::add_image_rotations(angles, images, bboxes);
    dlib::image_window window;

    for (auto i = 0; i < images.size(); i++) {
        window.set_image(images[i]);
        window.clear_overlay();
        window.add_overlay(bboxes[i]);
        window.show();

        std::cin.get();
    }
```


from interpolation.h
```
 inline rectangle tform_object (
            const point_transform_affine& tran,
            const rectangle& rect
        )
        {
            return centered_rect(tran(center(rect)), rect.width(), rect.height());
        }
```

when i changed it into below, this problem was fixed. (i saw below code from imglab)
```
         inline rectangle tform_object (
            const point_transform_affine& tran,
            const rectangle& rect
        ){
            dlib::rectangle newrect;
            newrect += tran(rect.tl_corner());
            newrect += tran(rect.tr_corner());
            newrect += tran(rect.bl_corner());
            newrect += tran(rect.br_corner());
            const auto ratio = std::sqrt(rect.area() / (double)newrect.area());
            newrect = centered_rect(newrect, newrect.width()*ratio, newrect.height()*ratio);
            return newrect;
        }

```
